{
  "texts": [
    "Another form of optical microscopy employed extensively within paleontology is polarizing microscopy, whereby specimens prepared as 30 micron thick thin sections are studied via sample rotation under transmitted plane or cross-polarised (PPL/XPL) light, with optical properties such as pleochroism, relief, birefringence, interferance color spectra and extinction angle facilitating the identification of mineral phases.",
    "Optical microscopy is valued for its simplicity, low cost, and widespread availability in educational (Kuo and Leo 2019) and research settings (Török and Kao 2007), producing large legacy datasets that encompass decades of image capture.",
    "Thus, a major advantage of OM is its ability to provide relatively high-resolution RGB images suitable for detailed fossil characterization both cheaply and efficiently.",
    "However, its resolution is limited by the diffraction limit, which is dependant upon the wavelength of visible light and the numerical aperture of the optical system, making the approach unsuitable for mapping submicron to nanoscale features (Smolyaninov 2008).",
    "While OM's accessibility and negligible requirement for sample preparation facilitates rapid data generation beneficial for DL model training (Hohlbein et al. 2022), the output images common exhibit considerable variability in quality, often due to the ad hoc nature of sample preparation and optical system set up, resulting in uneven illumination, blur and background noise, which may prove challenging towards DL model integration."
  ]
}